        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>How to Make a Deal with Ransomware Attackers</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As the number of ransomware assaults increases around the world, so does the demand for negotiation services, which is difficult to meet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Criminals are becoming increasingly adept at profiting from their access to your network.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They target a company encrypts all its data and then demand payment in exchange for its releaseoften in the hundreds of thousands of dollars.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ideally, you'll be able to retrieve your data from backups or break the encryption, but in many situations, the bad guys purposefully seek out and destroy backups, and their ransomware employs cutting-edge encryption. ##</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your data is being held hostage by hackers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So, what's next?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Companies must respond immediately to assess the potential for harm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are various varieties of ransomware, some of which are more damaging than others, and the ransoms requested range from a few hundred dollars to millions of dollars.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>New strains that infect entire systems, including backup data, are the most dangerous.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Companies should analyze whether they can reduce the problem without having to pay hackers, according to experts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is it possible, for example, to resolve the problem by restoring data from a backup source?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is it possible for security specialists to "hack back" or decrypt the data?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The financial costs of not paying up, as well as the chance that after paying, the company's data would not be restored, will be considered when deciding whether to pay a ransom, which the FBI advises against.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Another alternative is to involve law enforcement early, but the risks of exposing the incident to a potentially large audience must be evaluated against the resources and expertise they can contribute. ##</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When you decide to pay the ransom, what happens next?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>How do you reclaim your data while dealing with unscrupulous and perhaps unpredictable adversaries?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Suggestions for achieving the greatest results, as well as typical blunders to avoid. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pretend to be someone else** or try to deceive the assailants in any way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Criminals these days will typically probe your network for weeks or even months before installing ransomware and enslaving you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They will learn about your company throughout this period.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The criminals wanted a $200,000 ransomware payment in one example.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The firm stated that they could only afford to pay $60,000 in response.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Not according to your financials, the criminals retorted quickly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_24</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Attempting to deceive the attacker makes ransomware negotiations more difficult.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_25</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In another instance, the company's IT administrator pretended to be a high school student and said that a ransom of a few hundred dollars was all he could afford.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_26</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The crooks understood this was a fabrication.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_27</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>"They seem to have little patience for 'game playing."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_28</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If they see that kind of behaviour, they'll just dismiss you and move on to the next possible payer without responding. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_29</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't make promises you can't keep**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_30</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It may sound absurd, but in a ransomware discussion, a certain level of mutual trust is essential.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_31</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Stick to your word if you make a promise to the criminals, such as transferring the money by a certain date.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_32</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Otherwise, they may decide to stop replying or even act against you by revealing your information.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_33</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This was seen in a high-profile case involving an orthopaedic clinic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_34</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>According to DataBreaches.net, at various moments, \[the clinic\] said that it was willing to pay some ransom, but that it needed to work out a payment system.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_35</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They later stated that they were willing to make a wire transfer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_36</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They also failed to meet deadlines set by \[the crooks\], which enraged the hackers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_37</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some of the public leaks of patient data were a direct result of \[the clinic\] failing to accomplish what it said it would do when it promised the hackers. **'</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_38</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Proof of life' should be required.**</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_39</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>How do you know that if you pay, the crooks will be able to decrypt your data?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_40</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>New ransomware packages have invaded the darknet markets, some of which are poorly crafted and may accidentally damage your data.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_41</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other times, unorganized crooks may not have your key or be aware of how to utilize it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_42</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Professional negotiators have made it regular practice to demand "proof of life," requiring offenders to decode a test file to demonstrate their ability.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_43</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Avoid using this as an opportunity to dupe hackers into decrypting a vital file like your company's QuickBooks database: Criminals are aware of this and may become enraged as a result. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_44</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Engage the help of an expert**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_45</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To say the least, negotiating a ransomware payment is difficult.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_46</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're being held hostage, enlist the assistance of a skilled ransomware negotiator. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_47</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Treat a ransomware discussion as if it were a business transaction**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_48</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act composed, rational, and logical.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_49</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's a business deal for the crooks and handling it that way increases your chances of getting the best possible result for your company.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_50</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, frequently offers to make a smaller but faster payment: I can get X amount approved and have the money to you by tomorrow, implying that a larger ransomware payment will take longer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_51</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Criminals will often take a smaller payment if they believe they will receive their money sooner. ##</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_52</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What does the ransom payment entail?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_53</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Not as thrilling as in heist films.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_54</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Payment is mostly made by sending virtual money to an anonymous digital wallet, while there are few examples of difficult-to-trace methods like gift cards, according to experts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_55</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Because most businesses do not have cryptocurrencies on their balance sheets, they may want to set up a fund or enlist the help of a third party to do so. ##</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_56</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>How can you be sure that doesn't happen again?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_57</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Patching the company's software that is, ensuring it is updated with the newest updates is the first step in blocking prospective attacks.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_58</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Another option is to make backups of company files and store them apart from existing data.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_59</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Have a robust back-up program that is physically and conceptually segregated from the network and test it periodically.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_60</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Companies may want to build a doomsday scenario and do stress tests on it on a regular basis to guarantee that it works.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_61</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ideally, an organization would spend in developing a significant incident response strategy with clearly defined roles and duties aligned to various situations before a ransomware attack occurs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1694_5_62</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As the number of ransomware assaults increases around the world, so does the demand for negotiation services, which is difficult to meet. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
